Question 4:
Tables & Attributes
We will have 6 tables: Users, TimeEntries, Report, TimeEntryReport, TimePlans, TimeEntryPlan, TimePlansReport

We will have 7 tables:
Users, TimeEntries, Reports, TimeEntryReports, TimePlans, TimeEntryPlans, TimePlansReports

1. Users

id (primary key)
name (string)
email (string)
created_at (datetime)
updated_at (datetime)
2. TimeEntries (tracks time spent on activities)

id (primary key)
user_id (foreign key) (references users)
activity_name (string)
duration_minutes (integer)
activity_date (date)
created_at (datetime)
updated_at (datetime)
3. Reports

id (primary key)
name (string)
time_period (datetime)
created_at (datetime)
updated_at (datetime)
4. TimeEntryReports (join table for many-to-many between TimeEntries and Reports)

id (primary key)
time_entry_id (foreign key) (references time_entries)
report_id (foreign key) (references reports)
created_at (datetime)
updated_at (datetime)
5. TimePlans

id (primary key)
user_id (foreign key) (references users)
time_period (datetime)
time_plan_amount (integer)
created_at (datetime)
updated_at (datetime)
6. TimeEntryPlans (join table for many-to-many between TimeEntries and TimePlans)

id (primary key)
time_entry_id (foreign key) (references time_entries)
time_plan_id (foreign key) (references time_plans)
created_at (datetime)
updated_at (datetime)
7. TimePlansReports (join table for many-to-many between TimePlans and Reports)

id (primary key)
time_plan_id (foreign key) (references time_plans)
report_id (foreign key) (references reports)
created_at (datetime)
updated_at (datetime)
Relationships
A User has many TimeEntries
A User has many TimePlans
A TimeEntry belongs to a User
A TimeEntry has many Reports through TimeEntryReports
A TimePlan belongs to a User
A TimePlan has many Reports through TimePlansReports
A TimeEntry has many TimePlans through TimeEntryPlans
